Using the dashboard provided in the question, I compared the figures for Denmark, France, Norway, Austria, Sweden and Germany. There is an interesting behavior in all cases but Denmark: in the last six months, the proportion of people with only one dose constantly decreases. This might seem obvious since most people who got the first dose will get the second one; however, this could also mean that the vaccination rate is slowing for good, probably approaching a ceiling level for the country. I suspect the anomaly for Denmark that happened in Nov 2021 is due to the introduction of a new population: children 5-11 years old (https://abcnews.go.com/Health/wireStory/denmark-officials-reason-give-covid-vaccines-82822229). That boosted the vaccination rate, but then it plateaued in two-months time. All of this to say that I believe the only significant game changer to increase the percentage by 5% or more would be the introduction of a new population. And according to the German site, almost all the people who got the first dose have already gotten the second one, including children 5-11 (https://impfdashboard.de/).

I don't expect another major push for vaccines before the first of June. Especially as summer is approaching and the conversations around COVID are decreasing (even though cases are going up again). It's a new normal.

74.8% are fully vaccinated; 75.0% will be reached soon. 76.0% have received at least one dose, with somewhere between roughly 0.10% and 0.15% being added each week. If 0.15% are added each week, then the number of people who will have received at least one dose by June 1 will be 76.0% + (15 weeks) * 0.15% = 78.3%, and the percent fully vaccinated is by definition less than that. First doses are slowing down; ~0.35% of the population received a first dose in the past week, and the total for first doses is now at 75.4% (almost 75.5%). At this rate, 1.4% would become fully vaccinated every 4 weeks starting 3 weeks from now. 0.5% became fully vaxxed in the past week. 18w2d=18.3w remain in the forecast. If vaccine uptake remained constant at this level, then approx. 73.4% (total fully vaxxed on Jan 24) + 0.5% * 2 weeks (the next 2 weeks) + 0.4% * 1 week (the week after that) + 0.35% * 15.3 weeks = 73.4% + 6.3% = 79.7% would be the total on June 1. (It could be closer to 80% due to rounding errors.) But I think we can expect vaccine uptake to continue to fall off, especially as Omicron vaccines start to become available this spring. And it doesn't look like a vaccine mandate will be in place by June 1, as negotiations will take time in Parliament; if a vaccine mandate is successful, it is expected to be in place in the fall. So, I'm increasing my forecast further on bin 3.

Data and vaccination speed from e.g. Saxony is sobering. Vaccine mandate will arrive later than expected, if ever. Cities such as Bremen, which claimed to have the highest rate in fully vaccinated adults across Germany, has the fastest spread in omicron cases recently. This points to two issues: high vaccination rates tend to mull the fully vaccinated share of populations in a false sense of security, which in turn tends to accelerate the spread of highly transmissible variants through risky behavior. Secondly, for the future this could deliver an argument to people skeptic of the value of vaccinations, since the expected high level occurence of breakthrough infections will even out the urge to get first and second shots. The correct percentage is going to get more difficult to predict, since it largely depends on the final conditions and the effective date of any form of future vaccine mandates and can vary much for supply, seasonal and event driven reasons. However, it seems the forecast can nevertheless be narrowed down increasingly to the fourth bin, since new first doses are applied at a by and large constant and consistent rate at the moment and the current target rate the government has laid out (including people 5 years and older as far as I understand) is 80% as a foundation for stopping the spread of SARS-CoV-2 with a pandemic character. The uptake among school children, whose vaccination campaign has started just before Christmas, appears to be quick and promising - logistics currently still seem to be the root cause of delays.

Current rate => 70-71% by the end of the year, plus a few % more (5-10%?) by the end of the forecast period. 72.8% have had at least one dose. Vaccinating ages 5-11 may add ~1.5% to 3% in the forecast period. The incoming Chancellor wants to have a vaccine mandate in place with deadlines in Feb or March, but that may or may not happen. If Parliament passes it, it would likely be applied to age 14+, which is just under 88% of the population. So if a vaccine mandate is passed, it's quite conceivable that >85% (~85% age 14+ + 1.5% to 3% age 5-13) could be fully vaccinated by the end of the forecast period. Omicron and possibly other variants complicate the situation. Zeroing out bin 2.

The term "fully vaccinated" is ambiguous since we know as a fact that the efficacy of vaccines diminish over time. Therefore "fully vaccinated" will require at least a third booster shot since people with only two doses will not qualify as "fully vaccinated" in June 2022. My answer is based on this reasoning. If the question would be "What percentage of Germany's population will have received a second shot against COVID-19 as of 1 June 2022?" my answer would be 75-80 %

Today, the reported percentage of fully vaccinated Germans is 67.17%.
